<TITLE> An uphill struggle to rise from ruin </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Chittagong, June 13 (bdnews24.com) Rescuers Wednesday pulled three more bodies from rubble, taking the landslide death count to 118 in the port city of Chittagong amid a gloomy forecast that the rivers across the country have been swelling. Deputy commissioner Shamim Ashraf told bdnews24.com that rescuers recovered three more bodies overnight. Rescuers continued to search for more bodies Wednessday morning, officials said. An official of the Fire Service and Civil Defence Tuesday feared that more bodies were trapped under tonnes of mud following Monday's landslides, triggered by torrents of rain. Search for bodies has intensified with rains easing and waters receding. About 500 injured people from Lebubagan, Kacharigona and Workshop area were being treated at a makeshift relief centre in Chittagong Cantonment. Of the injured, 47 were transferred to Chittagong Combined Military Hospital. Big chunks of mud from hills buried dozens of bamboo-and-tin-roofed homes built under the shadows of the hills Monday, causing such high casualties. Rescuers continued to search for victims Tuesday while local administration was struggling to bring order in the devastated city. Life in the battered metropolis virtually collapsed but residents Tuesday were trying to pick up the pieces, overlooking the havoc of the nature. Deputy commissioner Ashraf Shamim told bdnews24.com that schools, colleges, institutes and universities have been shut down. The dead include 10 of two families while 11 lost their lives when walls of their homes caved in. A man was electrocuted. The injured were admitted to Chittagong Combined Military Hospital and Chittagong Medical College Hospital. Chittagong CMH has been kept open to the injured for emergency treatment. The Chittagong office of bdnews24.com reports: As many as 21 people died in Hathazari, 10 of two families in Chittagong University and Bayezid Bostami areas, nine in Sekandarpara in Bhatiari, two in Moti Jharna area and three in Dhebarpar area. POWER IS BACK Power Development Board officials said some 24 substations and their feeder stations shutdown during the downpour resumed operations Monday evening. Nearly two-thirds of the city, including Hathazari, Bakolia, Halishahar and Pahartali areas, reeled under power outage. Authorities suspended power supply to the areas fearing electrocution. The port city had 397 mm of rains in the 24 hours to Tuesday noon. RIVERS CONTINUE TO RISE Rivers in Brahmaputra, Ganges and the Meghna basins Tuesday recorded a further rise, worsening the prevailing flash flood situation in the northeastern region. Out of 62 monitoring stations across the country, 35 stations recorded a rise in water levels Tuesday, the Flood Forecasting and Warning Centre said in a bulletin. The flood situation, set off by monsoon rain and onrush of waters from Indian hills and mountains, could deteriorate but intensity is expected to be low, the bulletin said. The riverswhere water levels continued to riseincluded Surma, Kushiara, Manu, Padma, Jamuna, Korotoa and Khowai. CA, ARMY CHIEF RUSH TO CHITTAGONG Chief adviser Fakhruddin Ahmed dashed to the port city Tuesday morning to go around the disaster-hit areas. The army chief, General Moeen U Ahmed, travelled to the city to see the devastation wrought by the landslides. "Our first job is to rescue, treat and help the affected people recover," Fakhruddin said to reporters in Kacharigona, one of the worst-hit areas in the city. He pledged measures to purge the commercial capital of the waterlogging problem. The interim government head promised to open probes into illegal hill-cutting to bring the offenders to justice. He said the army would evacuate people from vulnerable areas to safer places. From Shah Amanat International Airport, he drove straight to Lebubagan in Hathazari. Chittagong GOC Maj Gen Sinha Ibne Jamali filled him in on the aftermath of the landslides that killed some 100 people. Communications and disaster management adviser MA Matin, Chittagong divisional commissioner Mokhlesur Rahman and senior civil and military officials attended the briefing. The chief adviser went to Jahangir Line High School in Chittagong Cantonment where the army has opened a relief centre. Fakhruddin gave rice, biscuit, sari, lungi and Tk 3,000 in cash to affected people at the relief centre. He also went to see the injured at the CMH. Adviser Matin drove to the city by road around Monday midnight and sat immediately with officials of the district administration to coordinate the damage-limit operations. He went to see the injured under treatment at the Chittagong Medical College Hospital and the Combined Military Hospital. bdnews24.com/corr
